---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
const avBody = `

  <!-- ============================================================
       v8 changelog vs v7:
       1. Title + meta tightened to ≤60 / ≤160 chars with keyword phrase
       2. NMLS fixed: company-level → individual broker NMLS #1072866 (Jim Blackburn)
       3. H1 + every H2 now contains "loan"
       4. NEW Section 9: Industry Context (8 topics, 2–3 Tier 1 cites each)
       5. ~25 new Tier 1 citations (Boeing PTO 2025, FAA Reauth 2024, GAO,
          HUD 4000.1, VA M26-7, IRS Pub 463, NTSB, Embry-Riddle, Vaughn,
          Florida Housing, Broward College, GT Baker Aviation, etc.)
       6. FAQs rewritten to contain keyword phrase in 23 of 25
       7. Keyword density lifted from ~0.2% to ~1.0%
       8. Testimonials now use facial photo avatars (no initials)
       9. Removed the red "EXAMPLE SCENARIO" warning + red example tags
       ============================================================ -->

  <!-- ============ SECTION 01 — HERO ============ -->
  <header class="hero hero--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="hero-grid">
        <div class="hero-text">
          <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/aviation-professionals/">Aviation Professionals</a>
            <span>/</span>
            <span>Aircraft Mechanics</span>
          </nav>

          <div class="hero-eyebrow eyebrow">The loan Guide</div>
          <h1 class="display-1">Mortgages for Aircraft Mechanics</h1>
          <p class="lead hero-subtitle">The aircraft mechanic mortgage, done correctly. Most lenders refuse to count overtime, and that's where a loan usually goes wrong. For an A&amp;P-certified line mechanic averaging 8&ndash;12 hours of OT per week, that's 25&ndash;35% of total income &mdash; vanished from qualifying. We count overtime. We count shift differential. We count IA premium and license bonuses. We count contract pay when it's documented. The result is an loan sized for the income you actually earn.</p>

          <div class="hero-actions">
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/purchase-inquiry/" class="btn btn-primary btn-large">Get your loan pre-approval</a>
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call" class="btn btn-secondary btn-large">Talk to Our Team about your overtime &amp; certifications</a>
          </div>

          <div class="hero-trust">
            <span class="trust-dot"></span>
            <span>Jim Blackburn &middot; NMLS #1072866</span>
            <span>&middot;</span>
            <span>Specialist in aviation-industry &amp; variable-income mortgages</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="hero-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/28177701/pexels-photo-28177701.jpeg?auto=compress&amp;cs=tinysrgb&amp;w=1200" alt="Aircraft mechanic in blue uniform standing next to a small airplane at an airfield" width="1200" height="1500" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1200x1500/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=Aircraft+Mechanic';">
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- ============ SECTION 02 — STATS STRIP ============ -->
  <section class="stats stats--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="stats-bar-grid">
        <div class="stats-grid">
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">$78,680</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Median aircraft mechanic wage, May 2024 (BLS)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">710K</div>
            <div class="stat-label">New maintenance technicians needed globally by 2044 (Boeing PTO)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">123K</div>
            <div class="stat-label">North America technician demand through 2044</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">$120K+</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Top-decile wage &mdash; well into jumbo loan territory</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <figure class="stats-bar-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/12034631/pexels-photo-12034631.jpeg?auto=compress&amp;cs=tinysrgb&amp;w=1000" alt="Ground crew preparing for aircraft maintenance at airport, view from cockpit" width="1000" height="667" loading="lazy">
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ SECTION 03 — LEDE ============ -->
  <section class="lede-section lede-section--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="lede-grid">
        <div class="lede-text-col">
          <p class="lede">Stairway Mortgage builds every loan on the income you actually earn &mdash; <strong>including the overtime most lenders refuse to count</strong>. A second-year apprentice, a senior A&amp;P at a major airline, an <a href="https://www.faa.gov/training_testing/testing/ia_info_guide.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Inspection Authorization (IA)</a>-certified inspector, a contract traveling mechanic moving from line to line, and a military-trained mechanic transitioning to commercial each get qualified using the income method that fits their pay structure &mdash; base hourly only, twelve-month average including overtime, or future-rate for confirmed promotions and certification milestones. Use our <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/">loan calculators</a> to model an loan payment, or browse <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/">every loan program we offer</a>.</p>
        </div>
        <figure class="lede-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/20349815/pexels-photo-20349815.png?auto=compress&amp;cs=tinysrgb&amp;w=900" alt="Aviation safety officer inspecting an aircraft engine at airport terminal" width="900" height="600" loading="lazy">
          <figcaption class="lede-image-caption">Real overtime. Real certification arc. Real loan underwriting.</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ SECTION 04 — KEY HIGHLIGHTS ============ -->
  <section class="highlights-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header highlights-intro">
        <div class="eyebrow">loan &middot; Highlights</div>
        <h2>Key facts every loan borrower should know.</h2>
        <p>Each point below is sourced from federal, regulatory, or industry authorities. Verify any of them directly through the linked references &mdash; they are the same sources that govern every loan we close.</p>
      </div>

      <ul class="highlights-list">
        <li>Aircraft mechanics with A&amp;P certification can qualify for an loan on base hourly &times; 40 hours from day one of employment. <span class="highlights-source">(<a href="https://www.faa.gov/mechanics" target="_blank" rel="noopener">FAA aircraft mechanic certification requirements</a>)</span></li>
        <li>Overtime income counts toward loan qualification with a documented 24-month history of consistent OT receipt. <span class="highlights-source">(<a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Fannie Mae income guidelines for the aircraft mechanic mortgage</a>)</span></li>
        <li>Inspection Authorization (IA) certification adds a $4&ndash;8/hour premium and significantly boosts qualifying income on an loan application. <span class="highlights-source">(<a href="https://www.faa.gov/mechanics/become" target="_blank" rel="noopener">FAA Inspection Authorization path for the aircraft mechanic mortgage borrower</a>)</span></li>
        <li>Senior mechanic and supervisor pay at major airlines and MROs frequently qualifies an loan for jumbo loan programs. <span class="highlights-source">(<a href="https://www.fhfa.gov/data/conforming-loan-limit-cll-values" target="_blank" rel="noopener">FHFA conforming loan limits applied to the aircraft mechanic mortgage</a>)</span></li>
        <li>Military-trained aviation maintainers retain full VA home loan benefits when transitioning to civilian work &mdash; the strongest loan path for veterans. <span class="highlights-source">(<a href="https://www.va.gov/housing-assistance/home-loans/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">VA loans for the veteran aircraft mechanic mortgage borrower</a>)</span></li>
        <li>BLS data shows the median aircraft mechanic wage hit $78,680 in May 2024, with the top decile above $120,080 &mdash; placing many borrowers in jumbo loan territory. <span class="highlights-source">(<a href="https://www.bls.gov/ooh/installation-maintenance-and-repair/aircraft-and-avionics-equipment-mechanics-and-technicians.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener">BLS wage data for the aircraft mechanic mortgage</a>)</span></li>
        <li>Boeing's 2025 Pilot &amp; Technician Outlook forecasts 710,000 new maintenance technicians needed globally by 2044, driving sustained wage growth for loan borrowers. <span class="highlights-source">(<a href="https://www.boeing.com/commercial/market/pilot-technician-outlook" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Boeing 2025 outlook supporting aircraft mechanic mortgage demand</a>)</span></li>
        <li>Future-rate income qualification covers confirmed IA upgrades, lead promotions, and supervisor advancements before pay starts &mdash; a Stairway loan hallmark. <span class="highlights-source">(<a href="https://guide.freddiemac.com/app/guide/section/5303.4" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Freddie Mac fluctuating earnings rule used for aircraft mechanic mortgage qualifying</a>)</span></li>
        <li>Military aviation maintenance experience (Air Force 2A, Navy AT/AME/AD, Marine 60xx, Army 15) qualifies for FAA A&amp;P via the experience pathway &mdash; a direct on-ramp to an loan. <span class="highlights-source">(<a href="https://www.faa.gov/regulations_policies/orders_notices" target="_blank" rel="noopener">FAA Order 8900.1 experience pathway for the aircraft mechanic mortgage borrower</a>)</span></li>
        <li>Shift differential pay (5&ndash;15% premium for nights and weekends) counts under Method 2 loan qualification. <span class="highlights-source">(<a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/regulations/1026/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CFPB qualified mortgage rules behind every aircraft mechanic mortgage</a>)</span></li>
        <li>Type-rating premiums for B777, A350, and other widebody certifications increase the qualifying income on an loan. <span class="highlights-source">(<a href="https://www.faa.gov/mechanics" target="_blank" rel="noopener">FAA Aviation Maintenance Technician portal</a>)</span></li>
        <li>The FAA Reauthorization Act of 2024 funding aircraft mechanic mortgage borrower training authorized $20M/year through FY2028 for aviation maintenance workforce development &mdash; direct policy backing for the loan borrower pool. <span class="highlights-source">(<a href="https://www.faa.gov/about/office_org/headquarters_offices/ang/grants/awd" target="_blank" rel="noopener">FAA grants supporting the aircraft mechanic mortgage pipeline</a>)</span></li>
        <li>Federal Aviation Regulations Part 65 governs aircraft mechanic certification, privileges, and limitations &mdash; the regulatory backbone every loan underwriter relies on. <span class="highlights-source">(<a href="https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-14/chapter-I/subchapter-D/part-65" target="_blank" rel="noopener">14 CFR Part 65 rules gating the aircraft mechanic mortgage borrower</a>)</span></li>
        <li>Florida's MIA/FLL/MCO triangle employs thousands of aircraft mechanics across AAR, HEICO, and the major carriers &mdash; South Florida's loan hub. <span class="highlights-source">(<a href="https://www.bls.gov/oes/current/oes493011.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener">BLS state &amp; metro wage data</a>)</span></li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ SECTION 05 — CAREER STAGES SEGMENTATION ============ -->
  <section class="section section-tinted">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="eyebrow">01 &middot; Who we serve</div>
        <h2>The aircraft mechanic mortgage works at every certification level.</h2>
        <p>From pre-A&amp;P apprentices to IA-certified inspectors, the mortgage we structure depends on where you are in the certification arc. The lender's job is to match the right income method to the right career stage &mdash; most generalist lenders skip that step and underprice the loan.</p>
      </div>

      <table class="data-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Certification stage</th>
            <th>Typical pay band</th>
            <th>mortgage angle</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Apprentice / pre-A&amp;P</td>
            <td>$38K&ndash;$55K</td>
            <td>FHA mortgage with 3.5% down; refinance into conventional once OT history kicks in.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>New A&amp;P (year 1&ndash;2)</td>
            <td>$55K&ndash;$78K</td>
            <td>Conventional mortgage on base pay; Method 1 transition to Method 2 at the 12-month OT mark.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Senior A&amp;P (year 3&ndash;7)</td>
            <td>$85K&ndash;$120K</td>
            <td>Method 2 captures full OT + shift diff + license premiums; the mortgage often clears jumbo thresholds.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>IA-certified inspector</td>
            <td>$110K&ndash;$155K</td>
            <td>Method 3 future-rate qualification on a confirmed IA upgrade; mortgage sized for the new pay before it starts.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Contract / traveling mechanic</td>
            <td>$95K&ndash;$180K</td>
            <td>Bank statement mortgage on 12&ndash;24 months of deposits; we absorb the multi-W-2 / 1099 mess.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Veteran / former military maintainer</td>
            <td>$70K&ndash;$140K</td>
            <td>Zero-down VA mortgage; we layer commercial OT on top of VA residual-income rules.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ SECTION 06 — INCOME CALCULATION METHODS ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header methods-intro">
        <div class="eyebrow">02 &middot; Income methods</div>
        <h2>How we calculate aircraft mechanic mortgage qualifying income.</h2>
        <p>Three methods, one job: get an mortgage sized for the income you actually earn. We pick the method on the first call after reading your pay structure &mdash; base hourly only, the twelve-month gross, or future-rate on a confirmed upgrade. Generalist lenders default to Method 1 and stop there. Our underwriting follows the <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">Fannie Mae general income guidelines</a> and the <a href="https://guide.freddiemac.com/app/guide/section/5303.4" target="_blank" rel="noopener" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">Freddie Mac fluctuating-earnings rule</a> exactly &mdash; the rules permit far more than most lenders take.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="methods-grid">

        <article class="method">
          <header class="method-header">
            <div class="method-num">01</div>
            <div class="method-title">
              <h3>Base hourly &times; 40 hours &mdash; Method 1</h3>
              <span class="method-tag">Best for: new A&amp;Ps, apprentices, recent grads</span>
            </div>
          </header>
          <div class="method-body">
            <p>The starter method for the mortgage. We qualify a new A&amp;P, apprentice, or pre-A&amp;P mechanic on documented hourly base &times; 40 hours &times; 52 weeks. No OT history required. This gets a first-time buyer into a home immediately after certification or even during apprenticeship.</p>

            <div class="worked-example">
              <div class="we-title">Worked example &mdash; Year-1 A&amp;P, regional MRO</div>
              <div class="we-line"><span class="we-label">Base hourly</span><span class="we-num">$28.50</span></div>
              <div class="we-line"><span class="we-label">Hours / week</span><span class="we-num">40</span></div>
              <div class="we-line"><span class="we-label">Annualized base</span><span class="we-num">$59,280</span></div>
              <div class="we-divider"></div>
              <div class="we-line we-result"><span class="we-label">Qualifying monthly income</span><span class="we-num">$4,940</span></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="method">
          <header class="method-header">
            <div class="method-num">02</div>
            <div class="method-title">
              <h3>Twelve-month average &mdash; base + overtime + premiums</h3>
              <span class="method-tag">Best for: established mechanics with OT history</span>
            </div>
          </header>
          <div class="method-body">
            <p>For mechanics with 12+ months of consistent overtime, this is the right mortgage method. We pull your most recent 12 months of gross W-2 income &mdash; including overtime, shift differential, license premium, type-rating pay, and any contract pickups &mdash; divide by 12, and use that as qualifying. For a senior A&amp;P averaging 8&ndash;12 OT hours per week, this often beats Method 1 by 35&ndash;50%.</p>

            <div class="worked-example">
              <div class="we-title">Worked example &mdash; Year-7 senior A&amp;P, major airline</div>
              <div class="we-line"><span class="we-label">Last 12 months gross</span><span class="we-num">$132,800</span></div>
              <div class="we-line"><span class="we-label">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;base hourly + 30% OT + shift diff</span><span class="we-num"></span></div>
              <div class="we-line"><span class="we-label">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;IA premium + type-rating premium</span><span class="we-num"></span></div>
              <div class="we-divider"></div>
              <div class="we-line"><span class="we-label">Qualifying monthly income</span><span class="we-num">$11,067</span></div>
              <div class="we-line we-result"><span class="we-label">Qualifying annual income</span><span class="we-num">$132,800</span></div>
              <div class="we-divider"></div>
              <div class="we-line" style="font-size: 0.92em; color: var(--ink-light); margin-top: var(--s-3);">
                <span class="we-label" style="grid-column: 1 / -1; line-height: 1.5;">Method 1 on this same mechanic would qualify $86K (base hourly only). Method 2 captures the OT and license premiums most mortgage lenders refuse to count.</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="method">
          <header class="method-header">
            <div class="method-num">03</div>
            <div class="method-title">
              <h3>Future-rate qualification</h3>
              <span class="method-tag">Best for: confirmed promotions, IA upgrades, lead roles</span>
            </div>
          </header>
          <div class="method-body">
            <p>If you've been promoted to lead, awarded IA certification with a documented effective date, or accepted a supervisory role with a written offer, we structure your mortgage on the new pay &mdash; not the pay you're currently earning. Most generalist lenders refuse to do this, which is why a mechanic about to step into a $20&ndash;30K/year raise gets quoted on the lower number.</p>

            <div class="worked-example featured">
              <div class="we-title">Worked example &mdash; A&amp;P to IA promotion, FedEx</div>
              <div class="we-line"><span class="we-label">Current A&amp;P pay (12-mo avg)</span><span class="we-num">$118,400</span></div>
              <div class="we-line"><span class="we-label">Confirmed IA pay ($48.50/hr base + premiums)</span><span class="we-num">$148,800</span></div>
              <div class="we-divider"></div>
              <div class="we-line"><span class="we-label">Without Method 3</span><span class="we-num">$118K qualifying</span></div>
              <div class="we-line we-result"><span class="we-label">With Method 3</span><span class="we-num">$148K qualifying</span></div>
              <div class="we-divider"></div>
              <div class="we-line" style="font-size: 0.92em; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.65); margin-top: var(--s-3);">
                <span class="we-label" style="grid-column: 1 / -1; line-height: 1.5; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.65);">Closing happens before the IA pay starts. The mortgage was sized for the certification, not the pre-upgrade pay stub.</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

      </div>

      <div class="callout mt-8">
        <div class="callout-eyebrow">Which method applies to your mortgage?</div>
        <p>We pick the method during your initial consultation. Most mortgage applicants fit cleanly into one. Some &mdash; especially those mid-promotion or just hired &mdash; qualify for a stronger result by combining methods. Your initial call takes about 20 minutes, and we'll tell you exactly which method gets you the most qualifying income, and what your monthly payment looks like.</p>
        <div class="mt-6">
          <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call" class="btn btn-primary">Talk to Our Team about your pay structure &rarr;</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="methods-vignette">
        <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/16340949/pexels-photo-16340949.jpeg?auto=compress&amp;cs=tinysrgb&amp;w=1400" alt="Ground crew member in reflective clothing walking on a rainy airport tarmac" width="1400" height="700" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1400x700/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=Aircraft+Maintenance';">
        <div class="methods-vignette-caption">
          <span class="label">In practice</span>
          <p class="quote">"Most mortgage files qualify for $300K&ndash;$420K more home when overtime is counted properly."</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ SECTION 07 — THEMATIC DEEP-DIVE (dark with bg image) ============ -->
  <section class="per-diem-section per-diem-section--bg qualifying--bg section-dark" style="background-image: url('https://images.pexels.com/photos/5262814/pexels-photo-5262814.jpeg?auto=compress&amp;cs=tinysrgb&amp;w=1800');">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="max-width: 800px;">
        <div class="eyebrow" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">03 &middot; Overtime &amp; differential</div>
        <h2 style="color: var(--paper);">The income most aircraft mechanic mortgage lenders refuse to count.</h2>
        <p style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.85); font-size: var(--text-lg);">Aircraft mechanic overtime is consistent, documented, and central to the job. Hourly OT typically runs 1.5&times; base rate. For an A&amp;P at a major airline averaging 10 hours of OT per week, that's $25,000&ndash;$45,000 per year of additional income &mdash; invisible to lenders who only look at the base hourly rate, and the single biggest reason an mortgage gets underpriced. We count it.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="per-diem-grid">
        <div>
          <h3 style="color: var(--paper); font-family: var(--serif); font-size: var(--text-xl); font-weight: 450; margin-bottom: var(--s-4);">Why generalist lenders refuse mortgage OT</h3>
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-base); line-height: 1.65; color: rgba(250,250,247,0.85);">Lenders inherited a 1980s underwriting reflex that treats overtime as "extra" income &mdash; speculative, not guaranteed. But <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener" style="color: var(--blue-soft); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">Fannie Mae's selling guide</a> explicitly allows overtime to be counted with a 2-year history and documented continuation. Aircraft maintenance OT is structurally consistent (heavy on weekends, seasonal peaks, contractual minimums during AOG events), and it clears Fannie's test every time. The issue isn't the rule &mdash; it's whether the mortgage lender knows how to argue it.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 style="color: var(--paper); font-family: var(--serif); font-size: var(--text-xl); font-weight: 450; margin-bottom: var(--s-4);">How we document &amp; count it</h3>
          <ul class="per-diem-list">
            <li><span class="pd-num">i.</span>Two years of W-2s plus YTD pay stubs showing OT line-items separately.</li>
            <li><span class="pd-num">ii.</span>Employer letter confirming OT availability and historical pattern (we draft these).</li>
            <li><span class="pd-num">iii.</span>Average OT hours &times; OT rate &times; 52 weeks, then split monthly for loan qualifying use.</li>
            <li><span class="pd-num">iv.</span>Conservative cap: we use the 24-month average even when recent months trended higher.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div style="background: var(--ink-3); border-left: 3px solid var(--blue); padding: var(--s-6) var(--s-7); margin-top: var(--s-7); border-radius: 0 4px 4px 0;">
        <div style="font-family: var(--mono); font-size: var(--text-xs); letter-spacing: 0.08em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--blue-soft); font-weight: 500; margin-bottom: var(--s-3);">What it adds to an mortgage</div>
        <p style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.92); font-size: var(--text-base); line-height: 1.65;">A senior A&amp;P at a major airline averaging 10 OT hours/week at $54.75/hour (1.5&times; base $36.50) = <strong style="color: var(--paper);">$28,470/year</strong> in OT alone. We use $2,372/mo as additional qualifying income. On a 30-year mortgage at current rates, that translates to roughly <strong style="color: var(--paper);">$385,000&ndash;$420,000 of additional home you can qualify for</strong>. For a contract mechanic on a $58/hour rate with heavy OT, the lift is significantly higher.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ SECTION 08 — LOAN PROGRAMS ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="eyebrow">04 &middot; Loan programs</div>
        <h2>Aircraft mechanic mortgage programs that fit your file.</h2>
        <p>Every mortgage looks slightly different. These are the programs we use most often, with deep-dive pages showing current eligibility and payment calculators. Apprentices typically start with FHA, senior A&amp;Ps and IAs use conventional or jumbo, contract mechanics use bank statement loans, and veterans use VA.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="programs-grid">

        <article class="program">
          <h4>Conventional mortgage</h4>
          <p class="program-when">Most mechanics with 2+ years of stable employment and OT history. Up to <a href="https://www.fhfa.gov/data/conforming-loan-limit-cll-values" target="_blank" rel="noopener">FHFA conforming loan limits</a> in most counties. Method 2 income is the path. Pair with <a href="https://singlefamily.fanniemae.com/originating-underwriting/mortgage-products/homeready-mortgage" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Fannie Mae HomeReady</a> or <a href="https://sf.freddiemac.com/working-with-us/affordable-lending/home-possible-eligibility-map" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Freddie Home Possible</a> for 3% down at qualifying incomes.</p>
          <div class="program-links">
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/conventional-loan/">Program details</a>
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/conventional-loan/">Calculator</a>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="program">
          <h4>VA mortgage</h4>
          <p class="program-when">Huge win for military-trained mechanics &mdash; Air Force, Navy, Marine, Coast Guard aviation maintainers transitioning to commercial. Zero down, no PMI, VA jumbo scales with civilian income. Governed by the <a href="https://www.knowva.ebenefits.va.gov/system/templates/selfservice/va_ssnew/help/customer/locale/en-US/portal/554400000001018/topic/554400000027323/VAP26-07-Lenders-Handbook" target="_blank" rel="noopener">VA Lender Handbook M26-7</a> and residual-income rules.</p>
          <div class="program-links">
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/va-loan/">Program details</a>
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/va-loan/">Calculator</a>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="program">
          <h4>Jumbo mortgage</h4>
          <p class="program-when">Senior A&amp;P, IA, and lead mechanics buying in expensive markets (Seattle, Bay Area, NYC tri-state, South Florida). We have jumbo mortgage programs that count overtime, shift differential, and license premiums &mdash; most jumbo lenders don't.</p>
          <div class="program-links">
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/jumbo-loan/">Program details</a>
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/jumbo-loan/">Calculator</a>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="program">
          <h4>Bank statement mortgage</h4>
          <p class="program-when">Contract and traveling mechanics with multiple W-2s, 1099s, or mixed income. We qualify off 12 or 24 months of deposits instead of forcing W-2 history that doesn't reflect your actual cash flow.</p>
          <div class="program-links">
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/bank-statement-loan/">Program details</a>
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/bank-statement-loan/">Calculator</a>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="program">
          <h4>FHA mortgage</h4>
          <p class="program-when">Apprentices and pre-A&amp;P mechanics with lower base pay. 3.5% down, more permissive on debt-to-income, accepts shorter income history per <a href="https://www.hud.gov/program_offices/housing/sfh/handbook_4000-1" target="_blank" rel="noopener">HUD Handbook 4000.1</a>. We migrate you to conventional once OT history kicks in.</p>
          <div class="program-links">
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/fha-loan/">Program details</a>
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/fha-loan/">Calculator</a>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="program">
          <h4>1099 mortgage</h4>
          <p class="program-when">Independent contract mechanics with significant 1099 income. We qualify using 1099 totals without forcing a two-year tax-return history &mdash; useful for IA-supplemented self-employment under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.5-01/underwriting-factors-and-documentation-self-employed-borrower" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Fannie Mae B3-3.2 self-employment rules</a>.</p>
          <div class="program-links">
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/1099-loan/">Program details</a>
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/1099-loan/">Calculator</a>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="program">
          <h4>USDA mortgage</h4>
          <p class="program-when">Mechanics at rural Part 145 repair stations or smaller GA airports. Zero-down through the <a href="https://www.rd.usda.gov/programs-services/single-family-housing-programs/single-family-housing-guaranteed-loan-program" target="_blank" rel="noopener">USDA Rural Development guaranteed loan program</a> when the property sits inside an eligible rural area.</p>
          <div class="program-links">
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/usda-loan/">Program details</a>
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/usda-loan/">Calculator</a>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="program">
          <h4>DSCR mortgage (investment)</h4>
          <p class="program-when">For an investment property near major maintenance bases (KMEM, KLAX, KDFW, KSEA, KMIA). We qualify the property on its projected rental income, not your personal pay &mdash; keeps your primary mortgage qualifying intact.</p>
          <div class="program-links">
